dic = {
    "Fungal infection": "Fungal Infection. Fungal infections are caused by various types of fungi and can affect different parts of the body, such as the skin, nails, or genitals. Treatment options for fungal infections may include antifungal medications, topical creams or ointments, and proper hygiene practices. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis and personalized treatment options for fungal infections.",
    "Allergy": "Allergy. Allergies occur when the immune system reacts to certain substances, such as pollen, pet dander, or certain foods, triggering an allergic reaction. Treatment for allergies may involve avoiding known allergens, taking over-the-counter antihistamines, or receiving allergy shots. It is recommended to consult an allergist or healthcare professional for proper evaluation, allergy testing, and guidance on managing allergies effectively.",
    "GERD": "GERD (Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease). GERD is a chronic condition where stomach acid flows back into the esophagus, causing symptoms such as heartburn, chest pain, or regurgitation. Treatment options for GERD may include lifestyle modifications, such as avoiding trigger foods, losing weight, and elevating the head during sleep, as well as medications to reduce stomach acid. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis and personalized treatment options for GERD.",
    "Chronic cholestasis": "Chronic Cholestasis. Chronic cholestasis is a condition characterized by impaired bile flow from the liver. It can be caused by various factors, including liver diseases or certain medications. Treatment for chronic cholestasis may involve managing underlying liver conditions, relieving symptoms, and maintaining overall liver health. It is recommended to consult a gastroenterologist or hepatologist for accurate diagnosis and personalized treatment options for chronic cholestasis.",
    "Drug Reaction": "Drug Reaction. A drug reaction refers to an adverse or unexpected response to a medication. Symptoms of a drug reaction can vary and may include rash, itching, swelling, or more severe reactions. Treatment for drug reactions involves discontinuing the medication and managing symptoms, which may include antihistamines, corticosteroids, or other supportive measures. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and guidance in case of a drug reaction.",
    "Peptic ulcer disease": "Peptic Ulcer Disease. Peptic ulcer disease refers to the development of open sores in the lining of the stomach or upper part of the small intestine. Treatment for peptic ulcers may involve medications to reduce stomach acid, antibiotics to treat H. pylori infection (a common cause of ulcers), and lifestyle modifications. It is advisable to consult a gastroenterologist or healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis and personalized treatment options for peptic ulcer disease.",
    "AIDS": "AIDS (Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome). AIDS is a chronic condition caused by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV). Treatment for AIDS involves antiretroviral therapy (ART) to suppress the virus, manage symptoms, and prevent complications. It is crucial to consult a healthcare professional specializing in HIV/AIDS for accurate diagnosis, ongoing management, and support.",
    "Diabetes": "Diabetes. Diabetes is a chronic condition characterized by high blood sugar levels. Treatment for diabetes may involve lifestyle modifications, such as a healthy diet and regular exercise, as well as medication, insulin therapy, or other blood sugar-lowering medications. It is important to work with a healthcare professional, such as an endocrinologist or primary care physician, for accurate diagnosis, personalized management, and ongoing monitoring of diabetes.",
    "Gastroenteritis": "Gastroenteritis. Gastroenteritis, commonly known as the stomach flu, refers to inflammation of the stomach and intestines. Treatment for gastroenteritis involves rest, hydration to prevent dehydration, and symptomatic relief for nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and guidance, especially if symptoms are severe, persistent, or accompanied by other concerning signs.",
    "Bronchial Asthma": "Bronchial Asthma. Bronchial asthma is a chronic respiratory condition characterized by inflammation and narrowing of the airways, leading to wheezing, coughing, and difficulty breathing. Treatment for asthma involves avoiding triggers, using inhalers or other medications to control symptoms and prevent asthma attacks, and having a personalized asthma action plan. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional, such as a pulmonologist or allergist, for accurate diagnosis, appropriate treatment, and guidance on managing asthma effectively.",
    "Hypertension": "Hypertension. Hypertension, or high blood pressure, is a chronic condition characterized by elevated blood pressure levels. Treatment for hypertension may involve lifestyle modifications, such as a healthy diet, regular exercise, and stress management, as well as medication to control blood pressure. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized management, and regular monitoring of hypertension.",
    "Migraine": "Migraine. Migraine is a neurological condition characterized by recurrent severe headaches, often accompanied by other symptoms such as nausea, sensitivity to light or sound, and visual disturbances. Treatment for migraines may involve lifestyle modifications, pain-relieving medications, preventive medications, and self-care strategies. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional, such as a neurologist, for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment, and guidance on managing migraines effectively.",
    "Cervical spondylosis": "Cervical Spondylosis. Cervical spondylosis is a degenerative condition that affects the cervical spine, causing neck pain, stiffness, and sometimes radiating pain to the shoulders or arms. Treatment for cervical spondylosis may involve physical therapy, pain management techniques, lifestyle modifications, and, in some cases, surgery. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional, such as an orthopedic specialist or physiotherapist, for accurate diagnosis and personalized treatment options for cervical spondylosis.",
    "Paralysis (brain hemorrhage)": "Paralysis (Brain Hemorrhage). Paralysis can occur as a result of a brain hemorrhage, which is bleeding in the brain. Treatment for paralysis due to brain hemorrhage focuses on stabilizing the condition, managing symptoms, and preventing further complications. Rehabilitation, including physical therapy, occupational therapy, and speech therapy, may be necessary to regain function and improve quality of life. It is crucial to seek immediate medical attention in case of a suspected brain hemorrhage and follow the guidance of healthcare professionals.",
    "Jaundice": "Jaundice. Jaundice is a condition characterized by yellowing of the skin and eyes due to an excess of bilirubin in the blood. Treatment for jaundice depends on the underlying cause and may involve addressing liver dysfunction, managing symptoms, and supporting liver health through lifestyle modifications and medication. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, identification of the underlying cause, and appropriate treatment of jaundice.",
    "Malaria": "Malaria is a mosquito-borne infectious disease caused by parasites of the Plasmodium species. Symptoms typically include fever, chills, headache, muscle aches, and fatigue. Treatment for malaria involves antimalarial medications specific to the type of Plasmodium infection and its severity. The choice of medication may depend on factors such as the geographic region where the infection was acquired and drug resistance patterns. It is important to seek medical attention promptly for accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment of malaria.",
    "Chickenpox": "Chickenpox, also known as varicella, is a highly contagious viral infection caused by the varicella-zoster virus. It is characterized by a blister-like rash, fever, and general discomfort. Treatment for chickenpox focuses on relieving symptoms and preventing complications. This may include rest, over-the-counter pain relievers, antihistamines to reduce itching, and maintaining good hygiene practices. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional, especially for individuals at higher risk of severe illness, such as adults, pregnant women, or individuals with weakened immune systems.",
    "Dengue": "Dengue is a mosquito-borne viral infection caused by the dengue virus. It is characterized by symptoms such as high fever, severe headache, joint and muscle pain, rash, and in severe cases, dengue hemorrhagic fever or dengue shock syndrome. There is no specific treatment for dengue, and management involves supportive care, such as rest, fluid intake to prevent dehydration, and over-the-counter pain relievers. It is important to seek medical attention for accurate diagnosis, monitoring, and appropriate management of dengue, particularly for severe cases.",
    "Typhoid": "Typhoid fever is a bacterial infection caused by the bacterium Salmonella typhi. It is typically transmitted through contaminated food or water. Symptoms include sustained fever, headache, abdominal pain, and diarrhea or constipation. Treatment for typhoid fever usually involves antibiotics to eliminate the bacteria. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis and appropriate antibiotic therapy. In some cases, hospitalization may be necessary, especially for severe cases or complications. Hygiene practices and safe food and water consumption are important preventive measures.",
    "hepatitis A": "Hepatitis A is a viral infection that affects the liver and is transmitted through contaminated food or water. Symptoms of hepatitis A include fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes). Treatment for hepatitis A focuses on supportive care, such as rest, adequate nutrition, and avoiding substances that may further damage the liver. Most people recover from hepatitis A without specific treatment. However, it is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, monitoring, and guidance in managing hepatitis A. Vaccination is also available for prevention.",
    "Hepatitis B": "Hepatitis B. Hepatitis B is a viral infection that affects the liver. Treatment for hepatitis B may involve antiviral medications to suppress the virus and prevent liver damage. Regular monitoring of liver function and vaccination to prevent hepatitis B transmission are also important. It is crucial to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment, and guidance on hepatitis B management and prevention.",
    "Hepatitis C": "Hepatitis C. Hepatitis C is a viral infection that affects the liver. Treatment for hepatitis C has advanced significantly in recent years, and antiviral medications can cure the infection in many cases. The treatment regimen may vary depending on the specific genotype and other factors. It is important to consult a healthcare professional who specializes in hepatitis C for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing the condition.",
    "Hepatitis D": "Hepatitis D. Hepatitis D, also known as delta hepatitis, is a viral infection that occurs only in individuals who are already infected with hepatitis B. Treatment for hepatitis D focuses on managing the hepatitis B infection and may involve antiviral medications and regular monitoring of liver function. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment, and guidance on managing hepatitis D.",
    "Hepatitis E": "Hepatitis E. Hepatitis E is a viral infection that primarily spreads through contaminated water or food. In most cases, hepatitis E resolves on its own without specific treatment. Supportive care, such as rest, hydration, and a balanced diet, is important during recovery. Prevention through safe water and food practices, such as proper sanitation and hygiene, is crucial. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, proper management, and guidance on hepatitis E prevention strategies.",
    "Varicoseveins": "Varicose veins are swollen, twisted veins that commonly occur in the legs and can cause discomfort or pain. They result from weakened or damaged valves in the veins, leading to poor blood circulation. Treatment options for varicose veins may include lifestyle changes such as regular exercise, elevating the legs, and wearing compression stockings. In more severe cases, medical procedures like sclerotherapy or laser therapy may be recommended to close off or remove the affected veins. It is advisable to consult a vascular specialist or healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and personalized treatment options for varicose veins.",
    "Alcoholic hepatitis": "Alcoholic Hepatitis. Alcoholic hepatitis is inflammation of the liver caused by excessive alcohol consumption. Treatment for alcoholic hepatitis involves abstaining from alcohol and making lifestyle changes to improve liver health. Medications may be prescribed to manage symptoms and promote liver healing. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment, and guidance on managing alcoholic hepatitis.",
    "Tuberculosis": "Tuberculosis. Tuberculosis (TB) is a bacterial infection that primarily affects the lungs but can also affect other parts of the body. Treatment for tuberculosis involves a combination of antibiotics taken for a specific duration. It is crucial to complete the full course of treatment as prescribed by a healthcare professional to effectively cure the infection and prevent the development of drug-resistant strains. Regular monitoring and follow-up are important during treatment. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment, and guidance on managing tuberculosis.",
    "Common Cold": "Common Cold. The common cold is a viral infection that primarily affects the upper respiratory system. Treatment for the common cold focuses on managing symptoms, such as rest, staying hydrated, over-the-counter medications to relieve symptoms like fever and congestion, and using home remedies like warm liquids and saline nasal rinses. It is important to practice good hygiene, such as frequent handwashing, to prevent the spread of the cold virus. It is advisable to consult a healthcare professional if symptoms worsen or persist for an extended period.",
    "Pneumonia": "Pneumonia. Pneumonia is an infection that causes inflammation in the lungs. Treatment for pneumonia may involve antibiotics to fight the underlying bacterial infection, rest, hydration, and symptom management with over-the-counter medications for fever and cough. In severe cases or for individuals with a weakened immune system, hospitalization and intravenous antibiotics may be necessary. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment, and guidance on managing pneumonia.",
    "Dimorphic hemorrhoids (piles)": "Dimorphic Hemorrhoids (Piles). Hemorrhoids, also known as piles, are swollen veins in the lower rectum or anus. Treatment for hemorrhoids may involve lifestyle changes such as increasing fiber intake, drinking plenty of fluids, and practicing good bathroom habits. Over-the-counter creams, ointments, and suppositories can help relieve symptoms. In severe cases, procedures like rubber band ligation or surgery may be recommended. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing hemorrhoids.",
    "Heartattack": "Heart Attack. A heart attack, also known as a myocardial infarction, occurs when there is a blockage in the blood supply to the heart muscle. Immediate medical attention is crucial for a heart attack. Treatment may involve medications to relieve chest pain, restore blood flow, and prevent further complications. Procedures like angioplasty and stenting or bypass surgery may be necessary to restore blood flow to the heart. Cardiac rehabilitation and lifestyle changes are essential for long-term management. It is important to seek emergency medical care in the event of a suspected heart attack.",
    "Varicose veins": "Varicose Veins. Varicose veins are enlarged and twisted veins, usually in the legs. Treatment for varicose veins may involve lifestyle modifications such as regular exercise, elevating the legs, and wearing compression stockings to improve blood flow. Sclerotherapy, laser treatment, or surgical procedures may be recommended for symptomatic or severe cases. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing varicose veins.",
    "Hypothyroidism": "Hypothyroidism. Hypothyroidism is a condition characterized by an underactive thyroid gland, which leads to a decrease in the production of thyroid hormones. Treatment for hypothyroidism involves hormone replacement therapy with synthetic thyroid hormones. The dosage of medication is determined based on individual needs and is regularly monitored. It is important to follow up with a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, regular monitoring, and adjustments in medication as needed.",
    "Hyperthyroidism": "Hyperthyroidism. Hyperthyroidism is a condition characterized by an overactive thyroid gland, which leads to an excess production of thyroid hormones. Treatment for hyperthyroidism may involve medications that reduce thyroid hormone production or block their effects, radioactive iodine therapy, or in some cases, surgery to remove the thyroid gland. The choice of treatment depends on the underlying cause and individual circumstances. Regular monitoring and follow-up with a healthcare professional are important for managing hyperthyroidism effectively.",
    "Hypoglycemia": "Hypoglycemia. Hypoglycemia is a condition characterized by low blood sugar levels. Treatment for hypoglycemia depends on the underlying cause and severity. For individuals with diabetes, it may involve consuming fast-acting sources of glucose or carbohydrates to raise blood sugar levels. In some cases, adjusting medication dosages or making dietary and lifestyle changes may be necessary to prevent recurrent episodes. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing hypoglycemia.",
    "Osteoarthritis": "Osteoarthritis. Osteoarthritis is a degenerative joint disease that causes the breakdown of cartilage in the joints. Treatment for osteoarthritis may involve a combination of lifestyle changes, physical therapy, pain management, and medications to reduce inflammation and relieve symptoms. In some cases, joint replacement surgery may be recommended. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing osteoarthritis.",
    "Arthritis": "Arthritis. Arthritis is a broad term that refers to inflammation of one or more joints. Treatment for arthritis depends on the specific type and underlying cause. It may involve a combination of medication, physical therapy, lifestyle modifications, and assistive devices to manage pain, reduce inflammation, and improve joint function. The treatment plan is tailored to the individual's needs and may require ongoing management and monitoring. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing arthritis.",
    "(vertigo) Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo": "(Vertigo) Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo. Paroxysmal positional vertigo (PPV) is a type of vertigo that occurs when certain head movements trigger a sudden spinning sensation. Treatment for PPV may involve canalith repositioning maneuvers, such as the Epley maneuver or Semont maneuver, which help reposition displaced particles in the inner ear. Medications to alleviate symptoms and lifestyle modifications to minimize triggers may also be recommended. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing paroxysmal positional vertigo.",
    "Acne": "Acne. Acne is a common skin condition characterized by the presence of pimples, blackheads, and whiteheads. Treatment for acne depends on its severity and may involve topical creams or gels, oral medications, or a combination of both. Skincare practices, such as gentle cleansing and avoiding pore-clogging products, are also important. In some cases, procedures like chemical peels or laser therapy may be recommended. It is important to consult a dermatologist for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing acne.",
    "Urinary tract infection": "Urinary Tract Infection (UTI). A urinary tract infection is an infection that affects any part of the urinary system, including the kidneys, bladder, ureters, and urethra. Treatment for a UTI typically involves a course of antibiotics to eliminate the bacteria causing the infection. Drinking plenty of fluids and practicing good hygiene can also help manage and prevent UTIs. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing urinary tract infections.",
    "Psoriasis": "Psoriasis. Psoriasis is a chronic skin condition characterized by red, scaly patches on the skin. Treatment for psoriasis may involve topical treatments, such as corticosteroids or retinoids, phototherapy, systemic medications, or biologic therapies. Additionally, lifestyle modifications like moisturizing the skin, avoiding triggers, and managing stress can help reduce symptoms. It is important to consult a dermatologist for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing psoriasis.",
    "Impetigo": "Impetigo. Impetigo is a contagious skin infection that is commonly seen in children. Treatment for impetigo may involve topical or oral antibiotics to eliminate the bacteria causing the infection. Good hygiene practices, such as keeping the affected area clean and avoiding close contact with others, can help prevent the spread of impetigo. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized treatment options, and guidance on managing impetigo.",
}
